{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Animations","slug":"css-animations","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Advanced","estimated_read_time":"20 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Transitions"],"learning_objectives":["Understand @keyframes","animation-name","animation-duration","animation-delay","animation-iteration-count","animation-direction","animation-fill-mode"],"theory":"CSS Animations allow you to animate transitions from one CSS style configuration to another.\n\nThey consist of two components:\n1.  A style describing the CSS animation.\n2.  A set of keyframes that indicate the start and end states of the animation's style, as well as possible intermediate waypoints.","syntax":"@keyframes slide {\n  from { left: 0; }\n  to { left: 200px; }\n}\n\ndiv {\n  animation-name: slide;\n  animation-duration: 4s;\n}","examples":[{"code":"@keyframes spin {\n  0% { transform: rotate(0deg); }\n  100% { transform: rotate(360deg); }\n}\n\n.loader {\n  animation: spin 2s linear infinite;\n}","output":"An element that spins forever.","explanation":"Standard way to create loading spinners."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Forgetting duration","correction":"If `animation-duration` is not specified, it defaults to 0s, and the animation will not play.","example":""}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"Difference between `transition` and `animation`?","answer":"Transition requires a trigger (hover, focus, class change) and just goes A to B. Animation works automatically and can have infinite intermediate steps (keyframes) and loop.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Create a pulsing effect (scale up and down) that runs forever.","hint":"scale(1.1) and infinite alternate.","solution":"@keyframes pulse { 0% { transform: scale(1); } 100% { transform: scale(1.1); } } .box { animation: pulse 1s infinite alternate; }","difficulty":"Medium"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Welcome Animations","description":"Elements fading in and sliding up as